            "title": "r Minus g",
            "abstract": "Long-term data show that the dynamic efficiency condition <i>r>g</i> holds when <i>g</i> is represented by the average growth rate of real GDP if <i>r</i> is the average real rate of return on equity, <i>E(r<sup>e</sup>)</i>, but not if <i>r</i> is the risk-free rate, <i>r<sup>f</sup></i>.  This pattern accords with a simple disaster-risk model calibrated to fit observed equity premia.  If Ponzi (chain-letter) finance by private agents and the government are precluded, the equilibrium can feature <i>r<sup>f</sup>\u2264E(g)</i>, a result that does not signal dynamic inefficiency.  In contrast, <i>E(r<sup>e</sup>)>E(g)</i> is required for dynamic efficiency, implied by the model, and consistent with the data.  The model satisfies Ricardian Equivalence because, without Ponzi finance by the government, a rise in safe assets from increased public debt is matched by an increase in the safe (that is, certain) present value of liabilities associated with net taxes",
